# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: switching-regulator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] A **DC-to-DC converter** is an electronic circuit or electromechanical device that converts a source of direct current (DC) from one voltage level to another DC.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] It is a type of electric power converter.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Power levels range from very low (small batteries) to very high (high-voltage power transmission).
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the development of power semiconductors, one way to convert the voltage of a DC supply to a higher voltage, for low-power applications, was to convert it to AC by using a vibrator, then by a step-up transformer, and finally a rectifier.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Where higher power was needed, a motor–generator unit was often used, in which an electric motor drove a generator that produced the desired voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The introduction of power semiconductors and integrated circuits made it economically viable by use of techniques described below.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, first is converting the DC power supply to high-frequency AC as an input of a transformer - it is small, light, and cheap due to the high frequency — that changes the voltage which gets rectified back to DC.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Although by 1976 transistor car radio receivers did not require high voltages, some amateur radio operators continued to use vibrator supplies and dynamotors for mobile transceivers requiring high voltages even though transistorized power supplies were available.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] While it was possible to derive a *lower* voltage from a higher with a linear regulator or even a resistor, these methods dissipated the excess energy as heat; energy-efficient conversion became possible only with solid-state switch-mode circuits.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are used in portable electronic devices such as cellular phones and laptop computers, which are supplied with power from batteries primarily.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Such electronic devices often contain several sub-circuits, each with its own voltage level requirement different from that supplied by the battery or an external supply (sometimes higher or lower than the supply voltage).
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, the battery voltage declines as its stored energy is drained.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched DC to DC converters offer a method to increase voltage from a partially lowered battery voltage thereby saving space instead of using multiple batteries to accomplish the same thing.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converter circuits also regulate the output voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Some exceptions include high-efficiency LED power sources, which are a kind of DC to DC converter that regulates the current through the LEDs, and simple charge pumps which double or triple the output voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters which are designed to maximize the energy harvest for photovoltaic systems and for wind turbines are called power optimizers.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] In electric vehicles, DC-DC converters step down the high voltage of the propulsion battery to 12 volts to allow use of accessories such as lighting, climate control fans, entertainment electronics, and other systems.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] This converter may also recharge the 12 volt auxiliary battery used for startup and standby loads such as keyless entry or security systems while the vehicle is idle.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converters are designed to move power in only one direction, from dedicated input to output.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] However, all switching regulator topologies can be made bidirectional and able to move power in either direction by replacing all diodes with independently controlled active rectification.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] A bidirectional converter is useful, for example, in applications requiring regenerative braking of vehicles, where power is supplied *to* the wheels while driving, but supplied *by* the wheels when braking.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Although they require few components, switching converters are electronically complex.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Like all high-frequency circuits, their components must be carefully specified and physically arranged to achieve stable operation and to keep switching noise (EMI / RFI) at acceptable levels.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Their cost is higher than linear regulators in voltage-dropping applications, but their cost has been decreasing with advances in chip design.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are available as integrated circuits (ICs) requiring few additional components.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Converters are also available as complete hybrid circuit modules, ready for use within an electronic assembly.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Linear regulators which are used to output a stable DC independent of input voltage and output load from a higher but less stable input by dissipating excess volt-amperes as heat, could be described literally as DC-to-DC converters, but this is not usual usage.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] There are also simple capacitive voltage doubler and Dickson multiplier circuits using diodes and capacitors to multiply a DC voltage by an integer value, typically delivering only a small current.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] In these DC-to-DC converters, energy is periodically stored within and released from a magnetic field in an inductor or a transformer, typically within a frequency range of 300 kHz to 10 MHz.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] By adjusting the duty cycle of the charging voltage (that is, the ratio of the on/off times), the amount of power transferred to a load can be more easily controlled, though this control can also be applied to the input current, the output current, or to maintain constant power.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Transformer-based converters may provide isolation between input and output.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] In general, the term *DC-to-DC converter* refers to one of these switching converters.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] These circuits are the heart of a switched-mode power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] A converter may be designed to operate in continuous mode at high power, and in discontinuous mode at low power.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The half bridge and flyback topologies are similar in that energy stored in the magnetic core needs to be dissipated so that the core does not saturate.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Power transmission in a flyback circuit is limited by the amount of energy that can be stored in the core, while forward circuits are usually limited by the I/V characteristics of the switches.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Although MOSFET switches can tolerate simultaneous full current and voltage (although thermal stress and electromigration can shorten the MTBF), bipolar switches generally can't so require the use of a snubber (or two).
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] High-current systems often use multiphase converters, also called interleaved converters.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiphase regulators can have better ripple and better response times than single-phase regulators.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Many laptop and desktop motherboards include interleaved buck regulators, sometimes as a voltage regulator module.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Specific to these converters is that the energy flows in both directions of the converter.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] These converters are commonly used in various applications and they are connected between two levels of DC voltage, where energy is transferred from one level to another.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiple isolated bidirectional DC-to-DC converters are also commonly used in cases where galvanic isolation is needed.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched capacitor converters rely on alternately connecting capacitors to the input and output in differing topologies.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, a switched-capacitor reducing converter might charge two capacitors in series and then discharge them in parallel.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] This would produce the same output power (less that lost to efficiency of under 100%) at, ideally, half the input voltage and twice the current.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Because they operate on discrete quantities of charge, these are also sometimes referred to as charge pump converters.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] They are typically used in applications requiring relatively small currents, as at higher currents the increased efficiency and smaller size of switch-mode converters makes them a better choice.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] They are also used at extremely high voltages, as magnetics would break down at such voltages.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the availability of power electronics devices, electromechanical converters were commercially important.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] A motor–generator set consists of an electric motor and generator coupled together.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] A *dynamotor* combines both functions into a single unit with coils for both the motor and the generator functions wound around a single rotor; both coils share the same outer field coils or magnets.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Typically the motor coils are driven from a commutator on one end of the shaft, when the generator coils output to another commutator on the other end of the shaft.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The entire rotor and shaft assembly is smaller in size than a pair of machines, and may not have any exposed drive shafts.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Motor–generators can convert between any combination of DC and AC voltage and phase standards.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Large motor–generator sets were widely used to convert industrial amounts of power while smaller units were used to convert battery power (6, 12 or 24 V DC) to a high DC voltage, which was required to operate vacuum tube (thermionic valve) equipment.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] For lower-power requirements at voltages higher than supplied by a vehicle battery, vibrator or "buzzer" power supplies were used.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The vibrator oscillated mechanically, with contacts that switched the polarity of the battery many times per second, effectively converting DC to square wave AC, which could then be fed to a transformer of the required output voltage(s).
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Electronic converters eventually replaced electromechanical converters since they had no moving parts (aside from cooling fans), and were generally smaller, lighter, and eventually cheaper than electromechanical converters of similar rating.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are subject to different types of chaotic dynamics such as bifurcation, crisis, and intermittency.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage never reaches zero.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage may reach or cross zero.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] in continuous current mode, produce less harmonic noise than other switching converters.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Acceptable levels depend upon requirements, e.g. proximity to RF circuitry needs more suppression than simply meeting regulations.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] These may include a power control IC, coil, capacitor, and resistor; decreases mounting space with a small number of components in a single integrated solution.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The input voltage may have non-negligible noise.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, if the converter loads the input with sharp load edges, the converter can emit RF noise from the supplying power lines.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] This should be prevented with proper filtering in the input stage of the converter.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] The output of an ideal DC-to-DC converter is a flat, constant output voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] However, real converters produce a DC output upon which is superimposed some level of electrical noise.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Switching converters produce switching noise at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Some sensitive radio-frequency and analog circuits require a power supply with so little noise that it can only be provided by a linear regulator.
[src:switching-regulator/dc-to-dc-converter] Some analog circuits which require a power supply with relatively low noise can tolerate some of the less-noisy switching converters, e.g. using continuous triangular waveforms rather than square waves.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] PFM is a method of encoding analog signals into trains of square pulses and therefore has a wide variety of applications.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] There are practical difficulties in the design of electronics when working with non-fixed frequencies, such as transmission line effects in board layout and magnetic component selection, so generally, PWM mode is preferred.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] There are, however, select cases in which PFM mode is advantageous.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] PFM mode is a common technique for increasing the efficiency of switching step-down DC-DC converters (buck converters) when driving light loads.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] In medium to high loads, the DC resistance of buck converter switching elements tends to dominate the overall efficiency of the buck converter.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] When driving light loads, however, the effects of DC resistances are reduced and AC losses in the inductor, capacitor, and switching elements play a larger role in overall efficiency.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] This is especially true in discontinuous mode operation, in which the inductor current drops below zero, resulting in the discharging of the output capacitor and even higher switching losses.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] PFM mode operation allows the switching frequency to be reduced and for a control method that prevents the inductor current from dropping below zero during light loads.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] Rather than applying square pulses of varying widths to the inductor, square pulse trains with a fixed 50% duty cycle are used to charge the inductor to a predefined current limit then discharge the inductor current to, but not below, zero.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] The frequency of these pulse trains is then varied to produce the desired output voltage with the aid of the output filter capacitor.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] This allows for a number of switching loss savings.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] The inductor is given known levels of peak current, which, if chosen carefully in regards to saturation current, can reduce switching losses in its magnetic core.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] Since the inductor current is never allowed to fall below zero, the output filter capacitor is not discharged and does not have to be recharged with every switching cycle to maintain the proper output voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/pulse-frequency-modulation] All of this done at the expense of output voltage and current ripple, which increases as a result of the reduction in switching frequency and the gap between pulse trains.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A **switched-mode power supply** (**SMPS**), also called **switching-mode power supply**, **switch-mode power supply**, **switched power supply**, or simply **switcher**, is an electronic power supply that incorporates a switching regulator to convert electrical power efficiently.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Like other power supplies, a SMPS transfers power from a DC or AC source (often mains power, see AC adapter) to DC loads, such as a personal computer, while converting voltage and current characteristics.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Unlike a linear power supply, the pass transistor of a switching-mode supply continually switches between low-dissipation, full-on and full-off states, and spends very little time in the high-dissipation transitions, which minimizes wasted energy.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Voltage regulation is achieved by varying the ratio of on-to-off time (also known as duty cycle).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In contrast, a linear power supply regulates the output voltage by continually dissipating power in the pass transistor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The switched-mode power supply's higher electrical efficiency is an important advantage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies can also be substantially smaller and lighter than a linear supply because the transformer can be much smaller.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This is because it operates at a high switching frequency which ranges from several hundred kHz to several MHz in contrast to the 50 or 60 Hz mains frequency used by the transformer in a linear power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Despite the reduced transformer size, the power supply topology and electromagnetic compatibility requirements in commercial designs result in a usually much greater component count and corresponding circuit complexity.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching regulators are used as replacements for linear regulators when higher efficiency, smaller size or lighter weight is required.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] They are, however, more complicated; switching currents can cause electrical noise problems if not carefully suppressed, and simple designs may have a poor power factor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] is a mechanically switched version of a flyback boost converter; the transformer is the ignition coil.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] On 23 June, British inventor Philip Ray Coursey applies for a patent in his country and United States, for his "Electrical Condenser".
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Electromechanical relays are used to stabilize the voltage output of generators.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] (1966–1972), incorporated early switched-mode power supplies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] One of its applications is as a switched-mode regulator.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] starts using high-efficiency power supplies in its 7000-series oscilloscopes produced from about 1970 to 1995.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Robert Boschert develops simpler, low-cost switched-mode power supply circuits.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] By 1977, Boschert Inc. had grown to a 650-person company.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Robert Mammano, a co-founder of Silicon General Semiconductors, develops the first integrated circuit for SMPS control, model SG1524.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] is designed with a switched-mode power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] was designed with a switched-mode power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A linear power supply (non-SMPS) uses a linear regulator to provide the desired output voltage by dissipating power in ohmic losses (e.g., in a resistor or in the collector–emitter region of a pass transistor in its active mode).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A linear regulator regulates either output voltage or current by dissipating the electric power in the form of heat, and hence its maximum power efficiency is voltage-out divided by voltage-in since the voltage difference between input and output is wasted.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In contrast, a SMPS changes output voltage and current by switching ideally lossless storage elements, such as inductors and capacitors, between different electrical configurations.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In reality, these ideal components do not exist, so a switching power supply cannot be 100% efficient, but still provides a significant improvement in efficiency over a linear regulator.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Different switching configurations are used in SMPS designs.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A boost converter acts like a step-up transformer for DC signals.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A buck–boost converter works in a similar manner, but yields an output voltage which is opposite in polarity to the input voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Other buck circuits exist to boost the average output current with a reduction of voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The main advantage of the switching power supply is greater efficiency (up to ~98–99%) and associated lower heat generation than linear regulators because the switching transistor dissipates little power when acting as a switch.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Other advantages include smaller size and lighter weight from the elimination of heavy and expensive line-frequency transformers.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Standby power loss is often also reduced with the elimination of these transformers.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Disadvantages include greater complexity, the generation of high-amplitude, high-frequency energy that the low-pass filter must block to avoid electromagnetic interference (EMI), a ripple voltage at the switching frequency and its harmonic frequencies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Very low-cost SMPSs may couple electrical switching noise back onto the mains power line, causing interference with devices connected to the same AC circuit, such as audio equipment.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Non-power-factor-corrected SMPSs also cause harmonic distortion.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] There are two main types of regulated power supplies available: SMPS and linear.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] If the SMPS has an AC input, then the first stage is to convert the input to DC.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] An SMPS with a DC input does not require this stage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In some power supplies (mostly computer ATX power supplies), the rectifier circuit can be configured as a voltage doubler by the addition of a switch operated either manually or automatically.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This feature permits operation from power sources that are normally at 115 VAC or at 230 VAC.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The rectifier produces an unregulated DC voltage, which is then sent to a large filter capacitor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The current drawn from the mains supply by this rectifier circuit occurs in short pulses around the AC voltage peaks.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] These pulses have significant high frequency energy, which reduces the power factor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] To correct for this, many newer SMPS will use a special power factor correction (PFC) circuit to make the input current follow the sinusoidal shape of the AC input voltage, correcting the power factor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies that use active PFC usually are auto-ranging, supporting input voltages from 90–264 VAC, with no input voltage selector switch.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] An SMPS designed for AC input can usually be run from a DC supply, because the DC would pass through the rectifier unchanged.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] If the power supply is designed for 115 VAC and has no voltage selector switch, the required DC voltage would be 163 VDC (115 × √2).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This type of use may be harmful to the rectifier stage, however, as it will only use half of diodes in the rectifier for the full load.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This could possibly result in overheating of these components, causing them to fail prematurely.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] On the other hand, if the power supply has a voltage selector switch, based on the Delon circuit, for 115/230 V (computer ATX power supplies typically are in this category), the selector switch would have to be put in the 230 V position, and the required voltage would be 325 VDC (230 × √2).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The diodes in this type of power supply will handle the DC current just fine because they are rated to handle double the nominal input current when operated in the 115 V mode, due to the operation of the voltage doubler.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This is because the doubler, when in operation, uses only half of the bridge rectifier and runs twice as much current through it.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The inverter stage converts DC, whether directly from the input or from the rectifier stage described above, to AC by running it through a power oscillator, whose output transformer is very small with few windings, at a frequency of tens or hundreds of kilohertz.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The frequency is usually chosen to be above 20 kHz, to make it inaudible to humans.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The switching is implemented as a multistage (to achieve high gain) MOSFET amplifier.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] MOSFETs are a type of transistor with a low on-resistance and a high current-handling capacity.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] If the output is required to be isolated from the input, as is usually the case in mains power supplies, the inverted AC is used to drive the primary winding of a high-frequency transformer.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This converts the voltage up or down to the required output level on its secondary winding.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The output transformer in the block diagram serves this purpose.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] If a DC output is required, the AC output from the transformer is rectified.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For output voltages above ten volts or so, ordinary silicon diodes are commonly used.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For lower voltages, Schottky diodes are commonly used as the rectifier elements; they have the advantages of faster recovery times than silicon diodes (allowing low-loss operation at higher frequencies) and a lower voltage drop when conducting.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For even lower output voltages, MOSFETs may be used as synchronous rectifiers; compared to Schottky diodes, these have even lower conducting state voltage drops.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The rectified output is then smoothed by a filter consisting of inductors and capacitors.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For higher switching frequencies, components with lower capacitance and inductance are needed.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Simpler, non-isolated power supplies contain an inductor instead of a transformer.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This type includes *boost converters*, *buck converters*, and *buck–boost converters*.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] These belong to the simplest class of single input, single output converters which use one inductor and one active switch.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The buck converter reduces the input voltage in direct proportion to the ratio of conductive time to the total switching period, called the duty cycle.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For example, an ideal buck converter with a 10 V input operating at a 50% duty cycle will produce an average output voltage of 5 V.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A feedback control loop is employed to regulate the output voltage by varying the duty cycle to compensate for variations in input voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The output voltage of a boost converter is always greater than the input voltage and the buck–boost output voltage is inverted but can be greater than, equal to, or less than the magnitude of its input voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] There are many variations and extensions to this class of converters but these three form the basis of almost all isolated and non-isolated DC-to-DC converters.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] By adding a second inductor the Ćuk and SEPIC converters can be implemented, or, by adding additional active switches, various bridge converters can be realized.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Other types of SMPSs use a capacitor–diode voltage multiplier instead of inductors and transformers.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] These are mostly used for generating high voltages at low currents (*Cockcroft–Walton generator*).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The low voltage variant is called charge pump.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A feedback circuit monitors the output voltage and compares it with a reference voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Depending on design and safety requirements, the controller may contain an isolation mechanism (such as an opto-coupler) to isolate it from the DC output.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching supplies in computers, TVs and VCRs have these opto-couplers to tightly control the output voltage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The feedback circuit needs power to run before it can generate power, so an additional non-switching power supply for stand-by is added.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Any switched-mode power supply that gets its power from an AC power line (called an "off-line" converter) requires a transformer for galvanic isolation.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Some DC-to-DC converters may also include a transformer, although isolation may not be critical in these cases.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] SMPS transformers run at high frequencies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Most of the cost savings (and space savings) in off-line power supplies result from the smaller size of the high-frequency transformer compared to the 50/60 Hz transformers formerly used.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The terminal voltage of a transformer is proportional to the product of the core area, magnetic flux, and frequency.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] By using a much higher frequency, the core area (and so the mass of the core) can be greatly reduced.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] However, core losses increase at higher frequencies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Cores generally use ferrite material which has a low loss at the high frequencies and high flux densities used.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The laminated iron cores of lower-frequency (<400 Hz) transformers would be unacceptably lossy at switching frequencies of a few kilohertz.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Also, more energy is lost during transitions of the switching semiconductor at higher frequencies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Furthermore, more attention to the physical layout of the circuit board is required as parasitics become more significant, and the amount of electromagnetic interference will be more pronounced.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] At low frequencies (such as the line frequency of 50 or 60 Hz), designers can usually ignore the skin effect.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For these frequencies, the skin effect is only significant when the conductors are large, more than 0.3 inches (7.6 mm) in diameter.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switching power supplies must pay more attention to the skin effect because it is a source of power loss.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] At 500 kHz, the skin depth in copper is about 0.003 inches (0.076 mm) – a dimension smaller than the typical wires used in a power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The effective resistance of conductors increases, because current concentrates near the surface of the conductor and the inner portion carries less current than at low frequencies.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The skin effect is exacerbated by the harmonics present in the high-speed pulse-width modulation (PWM) switching waveforms.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The appropriate skin depth is not just the depth at the fundamental, but also the skin depths at the harmonics.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In addition to the skin effect, there is also a proximity effect, which is another source of power loss.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Simple off-line switched-mode power supplies incorporate a simple full-wave rectifier connected to a large energy-storing capacitor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Such SMPSs draw current from the AC line in short pulses when the mains instantaneous voltage exceeds the voltage across this capacitor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] During the remaining portion of the AC cycle the capacitor provides energy to the power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] As a result, the input current of such basic switched-mode power supplies has high harmonic content and relatively low power factor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This creates extra load on utility lines, increases heating of building wiring, the utility transformers, and standard AC electric motors, and may cause stability problems in some applications such as in emergency generator systems or aircraft generators.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Harmonics can be removed by filtering, but the filters are expensive.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Unlike displacement power factor created by linear inductive or capacitive loads, this distortion cannot be corrected by addition of a single linear component.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Additional circuits are required to counteract the effect of the brief current pulses.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Putting a current regulated boost chopper stage after the off-line rectifier (to charge the storage capacitor) can correct the power factor, but increases the complexity and cost.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In 2001, the European Union put into effect the standard IEC 61000-3-2 to set limits on the harmonics of the AC input current up to the 40th harmonic for equipment above 75 W.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The standard defines four classes of equipment depending on its type and current waveform.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The most rigorous limits (class D) are established for personal computers, computer monitors, and TV receivers.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] To comply with these requirements, modern switched-mode power supplies normally include an additional power factor correction (PFC) stage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies can be classified according to the circuit topology.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The most important distinction is between isolated converters and non-isolated ones.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Non-isolated converters are simplest, with the three basic types using a single inductor for energy storage.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In the voltage relation column, *D* is the duty cycle of the converter, and can vary from 0 to 1.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The input voltage (V1) is assumed to be greater than zero; if it is negative, for consistency, negate the output voltage (V2).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] When equipment is human-accessible, voltage limits of ≤ 30 V (r.m.s.) AC or ≤ 42.4 V peak or ≤ 60 V DC and power limits of 250 VA apply for safety certification (UL, CSA, VDE approval).
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The buck, boost, and buck–boost topologies are all strongly related.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Input, output and ground come together at one point.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] One of the three passes through an inductor on the way, while the other two pass through switches.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] One of the two switches must be active (e.g., a transistor), while the other can be a diode.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Sometimes, the topology can be changed simply by re-labeling the connections.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A 12 V input, 5 V output buck converter can be converted to a 7 V input, −5 V output buck–boost by grounding the *output* and taking the output from the *ground* pin.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Likewise, SEPIC and Zeta converters are both minor rearrangements of the Ćuk converter.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The neutral point clamped (NPC) topology is used in power supplies and active filters and is mentioned here for completeness.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switchers become less efficient as duty cycles become extremely short.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For large voltage changes, a transformer (isolated) topology may be better.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] All isolated topologies include a transformer, and thus can produce an output of higher or lower voltage than the input by adjusting the turns ratio.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For some topologies, multiple windings can be placed on the transformer to produce multiple output voltages.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Some converters use the transformer for energy storage, while others use a separate inductor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] By switching when a valley is detected, rather than at a fixed frequency, introduces a natural frequency jitter that spreads the RF emissions spectrum and reduces overall EMI.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Higher input voltage and synchronous rectification mode makes the conversion process more efficient.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The power consumption of the controller also has to be taken into account.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Higher switching frequency allows component sizes to be shrunk, but can produce more RFI.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A resonant forward converter produces the lowest EMI of any SMPS approach because it uses a soft-switching resonant waveform compared with conventional hard switching.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For every 10-15 °C beyond 25 °C, failure rate doubles.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Most failures can be attributed to improper design and poor component selections.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies with capacitors that have reached the end of their life or suffer from manufacturing defects such as the capacitor plague will fail eventually.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] When either the capacitance decreases or the ESR increases, the regulator compensates by increasing the switching frequency, thereby subjecting the switching semiconductors to ever greater thermal stress.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Eventually the switching semiconductors fail, usually in a conductive manner.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For power supplies without fail-safe protection, this may subject connected loads to the full input voltage and current, and wild oscillations can occur in the output.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Failure of the switching transistor is common.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Due to the large switching voltages this transistor must handle (around 325 V for a 230 VAC non-power-factor-corrected mains supply, otherwise usually around 390 V), these transistors often short out, in turn immediately blowing the main internal power fuse.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Power supplies in consumer products are frequently damaged by lightning strikes on power lines as well as internal short circuits caused by insects attracted to the heat and electrostatic fields.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Those events may damage any part of the power supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The main filter capacitor will often store up to 325 volts long after the input power has been disconnected.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Not all power supplies contain a small "bleeder" resistor which slowly discharges the capacitor.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Contact with this capacitor can result in a severe electrical shock.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The primary and secondary sides may be connected with a capacitor to reduce EMI and compensate for various capacitive couplings in the converter circuit, where the transformer is one.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This may result in electric shock in some cases.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The current flowing from line or neutral through a 2 kΩ resistor to any accessible part must, according to IEC 60950, be less than 250 μA for IT equipment.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supply units (PSUs) in domestic products such as personal computers often have universal inputs, meaning that they can accept power from mains supplies throughout the world, although a manual voltage range switch may be required.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switch-mode power supplies can tolerate a wide range of power frequencies and voltages.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Due to their high volumes of production, mobile phone chargers have always been particularly cost-sensitive.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The first chargers were linear power supplies, but they quickly moved to the cost-effective ringing choke converter (RCC) SMPS topology, when new levels of efficiency were required.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] Switched-mode power supplies are used for DC-to-DC conversion as well.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In heavy vehicles that use a nominal 24 VDC cranking supply, 12 V for accessories may be furnished through a DC/DC switch-mode supply.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] This has the advantage over tapping the battery at the 12 V position (using half the cells) that the entire 12 V load is evenly divided between all cells of the 24 V battery.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] In industrial settings such as telecommunications racks, bulk power may be distributed at a low DC voltage (e.g. from a battery backup system) and individual equipment items will have DC/DC switched-mode converters to supply required voltages.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] A common use for switched-mode power supplies is an extra-low-voltage source for lighting.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] For this application, they are often called "electronic transformers".
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] The term *switch mode* was widely used until Motorola claimed ownership of the trademark SWITCHMODE for products aimed at the switching-mode power supply market and started to enforce its trademark.
[src:switching-regulator/switched-mode-power-supply] *Switching-mode power supply*, *switching power supply*, and *switching regulator* refer to this type of power supply.
